\details{
\subsection{What does this model do?}{

Gaussian Process (GP) models — commonly known as Kriging in geostatistics —
predict values at unobserved locations by leveraging spatial autocorrelation.
The model assumes observations are a realisation of a GP with a specified
covariance structure. The covariance structure is characterised by a
variogram model parameterised by \code{range}, \code{nugget}, and \code{sill}.
}

\subsection{Engines}{

The following engines are available:
\itemize{
\item \code{"gstat"} — Uses the \strong{gstat} package for variogram-based kriging
(ordinary, universal, and simple kriging). Supports spatiotemporal
kriging with a \code{time_col} engine argument.
\item \code{"fields"} — Uses the \strong{fields} package (\code{Krig}/\code{mKrig}) for spatial
kriging. Supports large datasets via \code{mKrig}.
\item \code{"GPvecchia"} — Uses the \strong{GPvecchia} package for Vecchia-approximated
GP inference, suitable for large spatial and spatiotemporal datasets via
\code{time_col}.
\item \code{"spNNGP"} — Uses the \strong{spNNGP} package for Nearest Neighbor Gaussian
Process models, scalable for large spatial datasets.
\item \code{"PrestoGP"} — Uses the \strong{PrestoGP} package for scalable penalized
spatiotemporal Gaussian process models with built-in missing-value
imputation and limit-of-detection handling.
}
}

